@vahidhashemian Awesome :) It's more work to get the KIP through, but I really think it is the right solution.

I would just start with the [KIP template](https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/KAFKA/KIP-Template), copy it, allocate a KIP number (on the [main KIP page](https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/KAFKA/Kafka+Improvement+Proposals)) and then just start filling in the text. I think the motivation will be clear given the discussion in this thread, but probably needs to be condensed to be very concise. The proposal is, I think, mostly straightforward. I think the compatibility section may need the most thorough discussion because we are talking about making a breaking semantic change in an interface that has been marked stable. In this section, we'll want to very clearly argue that the number of impacted users will be minimal to zero.

Both @hachikuji and I will be more than happy to review before sending out to the general kafka-dev list so we can try to iron out any kinks before circulating it more broadly.

@bbejeck 
1. Adding a topic does not seem to trigger a rebalance: hmm, this is not expected and may reveal a bug in the current implementation. My understanding is that, when a new topic is created, the underlying consumer will detect these new topics from refreshed metadata and send a new JoinGroup request to the coordinator, causing rebalance.
2. Upon a rebalance is triggered, upon `onPartitionRevoked` we will close all the tasks; and upon `onPartitionAssigned` we will create new tasks. So for both topic creation / deletion, the `StreamPartitionAssignor` should be triggered, which in turn triggers `PartitionGrouper`. I will look at your comments in #1410 trying to find out what was the issue.

@gfodor Some other observations:
1. on the `recordLatency` call, there is a bug in this computation `sensor.record((endNs - startNs) / 1000000, endNs);`, which should be `sensor.record(endNs - startNs, endNs / 1000000)`, and actually I'm thinking if we could save one `time.nanoseconds()` by doing sth. like:

```
        long startMs = time.milliseconds();
        try {
            inner.init(context, root);
        } finally {
            this.metrics.recordLatency(this.restoreTime, startMs, time.nanoseconds());
        }

        public void recordLatency(Sensor sensor, long startMs, long endNs) {
            sensor.record(endNs - startNs * 1000000, startMs);
        }
```
1. we can save one `time.millisecond` call by calling `sensors.pollTimeSensor.record(endPoll - startPoll, endPoll);` instead of `sensors.pollTimeSensor.record(endPoll - startPoll);` for cases like this; and similarly for `sensors.commitTimeSensor.record(time.milliseconds() - now);` we could do 

```
time = time.milliseconds();
sensors.commitTimeSensor.record(time - now, time);
```

etc.

EDIT on 1): actually `nanoseconds` and `milliseconds` are not directly comparable, and `milliseconds` may actually be more expensive than `nanoseconds`. So I think we should just do

```
public void recordLatency(Sensor sensor, long startMs, long endNs) {
        sensor.record(endNs - startNs);
}
```

and let it call `milliseconds` internally.
